    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "If you've checked the vacuum lines and found no leaks, it's time to consider other potential sources of air intake. One possibility is the PCV (Positive Crankcase Ventilation) valve. A malfunctioning PCV valve can allow excess air into the system, causing a lean condition. Check the PCV valve for any signs of clogging or damage and replace it if necessary. Another internal source to consider is the throttle body. A dirty or failing throttle body can lead to improper air flow, resulting in a lean mixture. Clean the throttle body and check for any signs of wear or damage. Additionally, inspect the EGR (Exhaust Gas Recirculation) valve and its passages. A clogged EGR valve can restrict exhaust flow, causing the engine to run lean. Clean the EGR valve and passages to ensure proper operation. Lastly, don't overlook the possibility of a vacuum leak from the engine's internal components. Use a smoke machine to introduce smoke into the intake system and observe where it escapes, which can help identify hidden leaks.",
